<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri 23 Mar 2007
From: Martyn Kirk <Martyn.Kirk@health.gov.au>

In the posting regarding _Cryptosporidium_ infections in South
Australia the editor indicates that it is not usual for
_Cryptosporidia_ to be spread from person-to-person. Our experience
in Australia, is that cryptosporidiosis is commonly spread from one
infected person to another as shown by case control studies and the
commonness of secondary spread in households (Robertson et al, 2002).
It is often assumed that _Cryptosporidium_ is predominantly a
waterborne parasitic infection because of well-publicised waterborne
disease outbreaks. Waterborne cryptosporidiosis is clearly important
where water supplies have become contaminated by animal waste (Smith
et al, 2006). However, the vast majority of cases of
cryptosporidiosis reported to health departments are sporadic with no
known source.
In Australia, outbreaks of waterborne disease of any aetiology are
rare. In 1998, Sydney residents were advised to boil water due to
concerns about contamination of the water supply with
_Cryptosporidium_, although numbers of oocysts in water were
subsequently thought to be overestimated and there were no associated
human infections.
Every 4-6 years, State and Territory health departments report major
community-wide outbreaks of cryptosporidiosis with some clustering of
cases occurring around swimming pools and petting zoos (Puech et al,
2001; Ashbolt et al, 2003). These community-wide increases are not
related to water supplies, as they cross multiple water supply
systems and a source cannot be identified for the majority of cases.
In reality, the 2 main modes of transmission operating for
_Cryptosporidium sp._ are from infected animals and infected people
to susceptible individuals. These 2 modes of transmission probably
reflect the 2 main species infecting humans: _C. hominis_ and _C.
parvum_ (Hunter et al, 2007).
References:
1. Robertson B, Sinclair MI, Forbes AB, Veitch M, Kirk M, Cunliffe D,
Willis J, Fairley CK: Case-control studies of sporadic
cryptosporidiosis in Melbourne and Adelaide, Australia. Epidemiol
Infect 2002 Jun;128(3):419-31.
2. Smith A, Reacher M, Smerdon W, Adak GK, Nichols G, Chalmers RM:
Outbreaks of waterborne infectious intestinal disease in England and
Wales, 1992-2003. Epidemiol Infect 2006 Dec;134(6):1141-9.
3. Puech MC, McAnulty JM, Lesjak M, Shaw N, Heron L, Watson JM: A
statewide outbreak of cryptosporidiosis in New South Wales associated
with swimming at public pools. Epidemiol Infect 2001 Jun;126(3):389-96.
4. Ashbolt RH, Coleman DJ, Misrachi A, Conti JM, Kirk MD: An outbreak
of cryptosporidiosis associated with an animal nursery at a regional
fair. Commun Dis Intell 2003;27(2):244-9.
5. Hunter PR, Hadfield SJ, Wilkinson D, Lake IR, Harrison FC,
Chalmers RM: Subtypes of _Cryptosporidium parvum_ in humans and
disease risk. Emerg Infect Dis 2007 Jan;13(1):82-8.
--
Martyn Kirk
Coordinating Epidemiologist
OzFoodNet
Office of Health Protection
Australian Government Department of Health & Ageing
<Martyn.Kirk@health.gov.au>
