[2]
Date: Thu 22 Mar 2007
From: Ann Koehler <ann.koehler@health.sa.gov.au>

We have a severe drought in South Australia at the moment, and
believe that more parents than usual will be bathing their children
in the same bathwater in order to conserve water.
I am surprised that you doubt that _Cryptosporidium_ is transmitted
by sources other than 'water such as a swimming pool'. In our
investigations we had quite a lot of cases where many family members
were sick, and where there had been no history of contact with
swimming or wading pools or other recreational water sources.
Some children had shared baths, and we believe this was implicated.
As _Cryptosporidium_ oocysts are infectious immediately they are
passed and people have watery diarrhoea, it would be highly unlikely
that person-to-person contact transmission does NOT occur -- as it
does with bacterial diarrhoeal illnesses.
I suggest you refer to the following case reports where
person-to-person transmission has been implicated:
1. Wolfson JS et al: Cryptosporidiosis in immunocompetent hosts. N
Engl J Med 1985;312:1278-82.
2. Alpert G et al: Outbreak of cryptosporidiosis in a day-care
center. Pediatrics 1986;77:152-157.
3. Heijbel H et al: Outbreak of diarrhea in a day care center with
spread to household members: the role of _Cryptosporidium_. Pediatr
Infect Dis J 1987;6:532-535.
4. Cordell RL et al: Cryptosporidiosis in child care settings: a
review of the literature and recommendations for prevention and
control. Pediatr Infect Dis J 1994;13:310-317.
5. Koch KL et al. Cryptosporidiosis in hospital personnel. Evidence
for person-to-person transmission. Ann Intern Med 1985;102:593-596.
There are quite a few additional reports of nosocomial outbreaks.
--
Dr Ann Koehler, BSc MBBS FRCPA MPH
Director and Consultant Microbiologist Communicable Disease Control
Branch Department of Health
L1/162 Grenfell St
Adelaide SA 5251
<ann.koehler@health.sa.gov.au>
[ProMED-mail thanks Martyn Kirk and Ann Koehler for their comments.
We agree that it is well documented that _Cryptosporidia_ can be
transmitted from person to person and we hereby pass the information
and the references to the different studies. - Mod.EP]
